The men and women behind their startup are working toward a common goal through innovation that’s supported by an aligned vision and a unified desire to impact the future of orthopedic medicine. Each member of their team understands the diverse challenges and adversities that are faced by people of all walks of life– and many of us have experienced their own joint injuries as a matter of course. Together, the BRACEUNDER team is taking action to create an entirely new set of tools for taking on these challenges. Recovery, rehabilitation, and injury prevention – they’re taking on these issues so that you can focus on what matters most to you. BRACEUNDER has grown to the point that they’re drawing talented team members from all over the world, but they’re keeping their production local. Every BRACEUNDER product is 100% made in the United States. From the very beginning, their products have been designed and manufactured right here in Chicago. BRACEUNDER empowers individuals through innovation and creating dynamic, custom products that allow people to fully engage with their bodies and create new ways to get better. Through continuous innovation, they create solutions that allow all people express their full potential and talents. BRACEUNDER applies action to the challenges faced by individuals of all walks of life, many who are overcoming physical injuries and barriers to their physical movement. Their products symbolize the journey of overcoming pain, trauma, and injuries; in order to self-create meaningful lives unhindered by external challenges and found in the field of success.

Description: Mekanika uses fusion, stabilization and or in combination to augment support of fusion, cages, and artificial discs.
Headquarters Regions: East Coast, Southern US
Full Description: Mekanika, founded by David Holmes, Chairman and Chief Science Officer, has invested over 20 years of R&D on the Mekanika Spinal Restabilization System, a revolutionary advancement in the diagnosis and treatment of spinal instability. The company was founded within the renowned University of Miami's Orthopaedic Surgery Department, where Mr. Holmes was Director of the Spine Biomechanics Research Lab. The Spinal Stiffness Gauge (SSG) was patented and developed to allow an accurate, objective, intra-operative, computer-based measurement of spine joint instability before and after spinal decompression. The SSG was used at the University of Miami in over 300 patients undergoing spine surgery to demonstrate the accuracy and value of the measurement, which may become the needed, essential definition of spinal instability used to guide and document the necessity for fusion, restabilization or just the decompression. A database of SSG measurements has been developed from the test results in 300 patients, and can be reviewed in the May 2002 issue of SPINE.
